{
  "card_id": "currency_pair",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Currency Pair",
  "aliases": [],
  "school": "General",
  "definition": "A quotation of two currencies where the first (base) is measured in units of the second (quote). For example, EUR/USD = 1.25 means 1 euro equals 1.25 US dollars. Pairs are categorized as major, minor, or exotic based on components and liquidity.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "A currency pair is represented by a six-letter symbol consisting of two three-letter ISO currency codes separated by a slash (e.g., EUR/USD).",
    "The base currency is the first code, and the quote currency is the second; the numeric quote indicates how many units of the quote are needed to buy one unit of the base.",
    "Major pairs always include the US dollar as one component (e.g., EUR/USD, USD/JPY); minor pairs are crosses of major non-USD currencies (e.g., EUR/GBP); exotic pairs pair a major with an emerging market currency (e.g., USD/TRY)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Traders speculate on a currency pair's exchange rate direction. Going long means buying the base while selling the quote, expecting the base to appreciate. Going short is the opposite. Major pairs offer high liquidity and lower costs, while exotic pairs often exhibit higher volatility and spreads. Understanding pip values, which may differ between pairs (e.g., JPY pairs), is essential for risk calculation.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing the base and quote currency order, leading to misinterpretation of price movement (e.g., thinking a rise in EUR/USD means USD strengthening).",
    "Assuming pip value is uniform across all pairs; it differs, for example, for JPY pairs where a pip is typically 0.01 instead of 0.0001.",
    "Choosing exotic pairs without accounting for their higher volatility and wider spreads, which can increase risk."
  ],
